---
/**
 * Tutorial 04 -- Server Streaming
 *
 * The client:stream directive connects a DOM element to a Server-Sent
 * Events (SSE) endpoint. When the server pushes messages, czap morphs
 * the element's DOM -- preserving scroll position, focus, and form state.
 *
 * This is czap's alternative to full-page re-renders or complex
 * WebSocket setups. The server sends structured JSON messages over SSE;
 * the directive applies them as DOM patches.
 *
 * In this tutorial you will:
 *   1. Understand the client:stream directive and its data attributes
 *   2. Learn the SSE message protocol (patch, snapshot, signal, heartbeat)
 *   3. See how DOM morphing preserves user state across updates
 *   4. Learn about reconnection with exponential backoff
 *   5. Handle stream lifecycle events (connected, morph, error)
 */

import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Server Streaming">

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 1: What is Server Streaming?
       ============================================================

       Traditional web apps re-render entire pages or use WebSockets
       for real-time updates. czap takes a middle path:

         1. Server sends SSE messages (simple HTTP, works everywhere)
         2. Client receives structured JSON (type + data)
         3. czap morphs the DOM (not innerHTML replace -- smart diff)
         4. Scroll position, focus, and form state are preserved

       This is particularly powerful for:
         - Live dashboards
         - Chat interfaces
         - Collaborative editing
         - Server-driven UI updates
  -->

  <h1>04 -- Server Streaming</h1>

  <p>
    The <code>client:stream</code> directive connects a DOM element to
    a Server-Sent Events (SSE) endpoint. When the server pushes new
    content, czap morphs the element's DOM while preserving scroll
    position, focus, and form state.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Key idea:</strong> SSE is simpler than WebSockets (plain HTTP,
    automatic reconnection, works through proxies). czap adds smart DOM
    morphing on top -- the server sends HTML patches, and the client applies
    them without destroying user state.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 2: The Markup

       To enable streaming on an element, you need two things:

       data-czap-stream-url="/api/feed"
         The SSE endpoint URL. The directive opens an EventSource
         to this URL when the element hydrates.

       client:stream
         The Astro client directive registered by @czap/astro.
         It tells Astro to load the stream hydration script.

       Optional attributes:

       data-czap-stream-artifact="my-artifact"
         Appended to the stream URL as a path segment. Useful when
         one endpoint serves multiple artifacts.

       data-czap-stream-morph="innerHTML" (default) or "outerHTML"
         Controls whether patches replace the element's inner content
         or the entire element including its wrapper.
  -->

  <h2>The Markup</h2>

  <pre><code>&lt;div
  data-czap-stream-url="/api/feed"
  data-czap-stream-morph="innerHTML"
  client:stream
&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Loading...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

  <p>
    That's it. The directive handles connection, parsing, morphing, and
    reconnection automatically.
  </p>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 3: The SSE Message Protocol

       The server sends JSON messages as SSE `data:` fields. Each
       message has a `type` that tells the directive what to do:

       "patch"
         Replace the element's content with the HTML in `data`.
         This is the most common message type.
         Example: { "type": "patch", "data": "<p>Updated</p>" }

       "snapshot"
         Like patch, but wraps the HTML in a `{ html: "..." }` object.
         Used for full-state snapshots (e.g., on reconnection).
         Example: { "type": "snapshot", "data": { "html": "<div>...</div>" } }

       "signal"
         Dispatches a custom event (czap:signal) on the element.
         Used for non-visual data (e.g., updating a counter, triggering
         a boundary re-evaluation).
         Example: { "type": "signal", "data": { "count": 42 } }

       "heartbeat"
         No-op. Keeps the connection alive through proxies/load balancers
         that close idle connections.
         Example: { "type": "heartbeat" }
  -->

  <h2>The SSE Protocol</h2>

  <p>
    Your server sends JSON messages over SSE. Each message has a
    <code>type</code> field that tells the directive what to do:
  </p>

  <pre><code>// Server-side: send a patch (Node.js example)
res.writeHead(200, {'{'}&br;
  'Content-Type': 'text/event-stream',
  'Cache-Control': 'no-cache',
  'Connection': 'keep-alive',
{'}'});

// Send an HTML patch -- replaces element innerHTML
res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
  type: 'patch',
  data: '&lt;p&gt;Updated at ' + new Date().toISOString() + '&lt;/p&gt;'
{'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);

// Send a snapshot -- full-state replacement
res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
  type: 'snapshot',
  data: {'{'} html: '&lt;div&gt;Full state here&lt;/div&gt;' {'}'}
{'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);

// Send a signal -- non-visual data, fires czap:signal event
res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
  type: 'signal',
  data: {'{'} count: 42, status: 'active' {'}'}
{'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);

// Send a heartbeat -- keeps connection alive
res.write(`data: ${'{'}&br;JSON.stringify({'{'}&br;
  type: 'heartbeat'
{'}'}){'}'}\\n\\n`);</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 4: Live Demo

       This demo element has client:stream pointed at /api/feed.
       Since there's no actual SSE server running in this tutorial,
       it will show the initial content and dispatch a
       czap:stream-disconnected event after the connection fails.

       In a real app, your server would send patches and this
       element's content would update in real time.
  -->

  <h2>Live Demo</h2>

  <p>
    The element below is wired to <code>/api/feed</code>. In a real app,
    it would receive live patches. Here it shows the initial fallback
    content (since no SSE server is running).
  </p>

  <!-- --------------------------------------------------------
       The streaming container.

       data-czap-stream-url: points to the SSE endpoint.
       client:stream: activates the stream directive.

       When the directive hydrates, it:
         1. Opens new EventSource("/api/feed")
         2. Listens for messages
         3. On "patch" type: replaces innerHTML, preserving scroll/focus
         4. On connection error: retries with exponential backoff
            (1s, 2s, 4s, 8s, ... up to 30s, max 10 attempts)
  -------------------------------------------------------- -->
  <div
    class="stream-target"
    id="stream-demo"
    data-czap-stream-url="/api/feed"
  >
    <!-- This initial content is what users see before the stream
         connects (or if the connection fails). Always provide
         meaningful fallback content. -->
    <p class="stream-status">Waiting for server stream...</p>
    <p>Connect a real SSE endpoint at <code>/api/feed</code> to see live updates.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 5: DOM Morphing Details

       When a patch arrives, the directive:

       1. Captures scroll positions of all scrollable descendants
       2. Records which element has focus
       3. Replaces innerHTML (or outerHTML) with the new HTML
       4. Restores scroll positions on elements that survived the morph
       5. Re-focuses the previously focused element (if still in DOM)
       6. Dispatches czap:stream-morph event on the container

       This means users typing in a form field inside the stream
       container won't lose their cursor position. Lists with scroll
       positions won't jump to the top. This is critical for
       usability in real-time UIs.
  -->

  <h2>DOM Morphing Preserves State</h2>

  <p>
    When a patch arrives, czap does not just slam <code>innerHTML</code>.
    It preserves user state:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Captures scroll positions of all scrollable descendants</li>
    <li>Records which element currently has focus</li>
    <li>Applies the HTML patch</li>
    <li>Restores scroll positions on surviving elements</li>
    <li>Re-focuses the previously focused element</li>
    <li>Dispatches <code>czap:stream-morph</code> event</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Why this matters:</strong> In a chat UI, the user might be
    scrolled up reading history while new messages arrive. Without scroll
    preservation, every patch would jump them to the top. czap handles
    this automatically.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 6: Reconnection

       The stream directive includes exponential backoff reconnection:

         - Initial delay: 1 second
         - Factor: 2x per attempt
         - Jitter: +/- 25% (prevents thundering herd)
         - Max delay: 30 seconds
         - Max attempts: 10

       After 10 failed attempts, it dispatches czap:stream-error
       with reason "max-reconnect-attempts" and stops trying.

       The directive also supports SSE lastEventId: if the server
       includes an `id:` field in its messages, the directive sends
       it back on reconnection so the server can resume from where
       it left off.
  -->

  <h2>Automatic Reconnection</h2>

  <pre><code>// Reconnection strategy (built into the directive):
//   Attempt 1: ~1s    (1000ms +/- 25% jitter)
//   Attempt 2: ~2s    (2000ms +/- 25% jitter)
//   Attempt 3: ~4s    (4000ms +/- 25% jitter)
//   ...
//   Attempt 10: ~30s  (capped at maxDelay)
//   After 10: gives up, fires czap:stream-error</code></pre>

  <p>
    The directive also tracks the SSE <code>lastEventId</code>. On
    reconnection, it appends <code>?lastEventId=...</code> to the URL
    so your server can resume from the last acknowledged message.
  </p>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 7: Lifecycle Events

       The directive dispatches custom events on the container
       element so you can react to stream lifecycle changes:

       czap:stream-connected    -- EventSource opened successfully
       czap:stream-morph        -- after a patch/snapshot is applied
       czap:stream-disconnected -- connection closed (before retry)
       czap:stream-error        -- max reconnection attempts exceeded
       czap:signal              -- server sent a "signal" type message
  -->

  <h2>Lifecycle Events</h2>

  <p>
    Listen for these custom events on the stream container:
  </p>

  <pre><code>const el = document.querySelector('[data-czap-stream-url]');

el.addEventListener('czap:stream-connected', () =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Stream connected');
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:stream-morph', () =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('DOM patched');
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:stream-disconnected', () =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Disconnected, will retry...');
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:stream-error', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Stream failed:', e.detail.reason);
{'}'});

el.addEventListener('czap:signal', (e) =&gt; {'{'}&br;
  console.log('Signal received:', e.detail);
{'}'});</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 8: Demo event listener

       This script listens for stream lifecycle events and updates
       the status text in the demo element.
  -->

  <script>
    const demo = document.getElementById('stream-demo');
    const status = demo?.querySelector('.stream-status');

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:stream-connected', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'Stream connected -- receiving patches...';
    });

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:stream-disconnected', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'Disconnected. Reconnecting...';
    });

    demo?.addEventListener('czap:stream-error', () => {
      if (status) status.textContent = 'Stream unavailable (no SSE server running for this demo).';
    });
  </script>

  <h2>What You Learned</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><code>client:stream</code> connects an element to an SSE endpoint.</li>
    <li><code>data-czap-stream-url</code> specifies the endpoint URL.</li>
    <li>The server sends JSON messages: patch, snapshot, signal, heartbeat.</li>
    <li>DOM morphing preserves scroll position, focus, and form state.</li>
    <li>Exponential backoff reconnection with jitter handles network issues.</li>
    <li>Lifecycle events let you react to connection state changes.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Next:</strong> <a href="/05-llm">05 -- LLM Streaming</a> --
    stream LLM tokens into the DOM with adaptive quality tiers.
  </p>

</Base>

<style>
  .stream-target {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 2px dashed #4f46e5;
    border-radius: 8px;
    margin: 1rem 0 2rem;
    min-height: 100px;
    background: #fafafe;
  }

  .stream-status {
    color: #4f46e5;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
</style>
